defaultDisproportionately affect migrants and children
default, and will
default therefore indirectly discriminate against those with a particular race, age, ethnicity or nationality. This has implications pursuant to th
defaulte Equality Act 2010 and Article 14 ECHR (when considered alongside Article 6 ECHR).
default&#xa0;
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDirectly discriminate against all children who do not meet the proposed test, including (
defaulti
default) British children under the age of 12 months who are unable to prove their citiz
defaultenship entitlement, (ii) migrant children who have been lawfully resident in the UK for less than 12 months and (iii) migrant children unlawfully resident in the UK who as minors without legal capacity or financial resources, cannot be held culpable for fa
defaultiling to seek to 
defaultregularise
default their status or seek privately- paid legal advice. It is no answer that local authorities can foot the financial bill, as in many cases such vulnerable and undocumented children will not be known to social services and even if t
defaulthey are, social workers are not immigration law experts and often do not 
defaultrecognise
default the advice needs of migrant children and young people. Local authority in- house teams are prohibited from providing immigration law advice, as advisors are not OISC registe
defaultred.
default There would also be serious questions regarding conflicts of interest and competing instructions if in-house local authority teams were to take on such work. 
